conversation_logs.reflection_content:
1. Proposal analysis  
• My proposal #1 won because it simultaneously maximized my own score (by pairing 2 with 0) and gave each counterpart at least one of the items they had publicly signaled interest in; it looked “fair” and required no concessions from them later.  
• haiku_agent_1’s proposal #2 failed hard: it was overtly self-favoring (took two high-value items) while giving haiku_agent_2 only 4 and carved up my set 0–1 in a way that weakened my score. No one had an incentive to approve.  
• haiku_agent_2’s proposal #3 gave me 0,3 (worse for me than #1 because I’d lose 2), took 2 for itself and gave 4 to haiku_agent_1; both haiku_agent_1 and I could do better, so we vetoed.

2. Voting patterns  
• Both haiku agents voted together: they accepted my plan and rejected the others. That implies their utility for my allocation was at least as good as status-quo alternatives.  
• They did NOT accept their own proposals, so either (a) they mis-estimated others’ tolerance or (b) their agents auto-reject if consensus is visibly impossible. Either way they are pragmatic rather than stubborn.

3. Communication insights  
• haiku_agent_2 is highly interested in item 4 and/or the 3-4 bundle (accepted #1 where it gets 3,4; rejected #2 where it only gets 4).  
• haiku_agent_1 was satisfied with just item 1, suggesting 1 is its key priority; willingness to drop 2-3 means it values harmony or has a steep drop-off after its top pick.  
• No one seems to value item 0 strongly except me; that’s useful leverage.

4. Strategic learnings  
What worked: framing a proposal that hits declared priorities, keeping a low-conflict tone, and seizing undervalued item 0 for extra utility.  
What didn’t: I revealed that 2 is important to me; future offers may try to ransom it back. I also played my strongest card early, which may raise expectations.

5. Future adjustments  
• Keep item 2 locked in, but be ready to trade 0 if I need goodwill later—others barely value it.
